vectorData.altText:
The lateral wall of the axilla is long and narrow; it is the floor of the intertubercular groove of the humerus. On the specimen, identify the borders of the intertubercular groove as follows: it is bordered medially by the tendon of insertion of the latissimus dorsi, and laterally by the tendon of insertion of the pectoralis major. On the Brachial Plexus specimen, the tendon of insertion of the pectoralis major will be cut.
The structures forming the walls of the axilla are again summarized here:
Identify the serratus anterior muscle on the lateral thoracic wall, making up the medial wall of the axilla     .

Now, identify the structures that make up the posterior wall of the axilla, the scapula clothed in the subscapularis, the teres major muscle and the latissimus dorsi muscle. When covered with skin, these form the posterior axillary fold. Identify, by palpation, your own posterior axillary fold     .
Place your supinated forearm on the table and push down on the table. Your latissimus dorsi and teres major will contract, and be easy to palpate.
